    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The Punishment of a False Witness. - To secure life and property against false accusations, Moses lays down the law in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 19:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that one witness only was not \"to rise up against any one with reference to any crime or sin, with every sin that one commits\" (i.e., to appear before a court of justice, or be accepted as sufficient), but everything was to be established upon the testimony of two or three witnesses. The rule laid down in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 17:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
